'''Westerham Common''', also known as '''Westerham Heath''', near [[Westerham]] in west [[Kent]], was a venue for [[cricket]] matches in the 18th century. These include two matches which are recognised for their historical significance, one of them classified as [[First-class cricket#Important matches classification|important]] by the ACS.<ref>ACS, ''Important Matches'', pp. 19 & 23.</ref>

On Thursday, 28 May 1730, a [[single wicket cricket|single wicket match]] between four men of [[Kent county cricket teams|Kent]], captained by [[Edwin Stead]], and four of [[Brentford Cricket Club|Brentford]] was played for [[Pound sign|£50]]. This was the first game in what became a tri-series.<ref>Buckley, p. 4.</ref><ref>Maun, volume 1, p. 41.</ref> On Friday, 10 June 1768, [[Caterham Cricket Club|Westerham and Caterham]], captained by [[Henry Rowett]], played [[Bourne Cricket Club|Bourne]], captained by [[Sir Horatio Mann, 2nd Baronet|Sir Horatio Mann]], in an important match which the home team won by 14 [[run (cricket)|runs]].<ref>Buckley, p. 56.</ref><ref>Maun, volume 2, p. 182.</ref> There are no records of important matches on the common after 1768.

